---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Editorial Standards"
  description="How Australian Home Collective writes, handles product claims and keeps commercial considerations separate from editorial judgement."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">How we write</p>
      <h1>Editorial Standards</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        These standards set out what readers should be able to expect from the site.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="content narrow">
    <p>
      Our aim is to help readers make sound decisions about products and problems around
      the home, including the decision not to buy.
    </p>

    <h2>How guides are written</h2>
    <p>
      A guide should answer the questions that could change the decision, such as:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>What should I measure first?</li>
      <li>What could stop this product from fitting?</li>
      <li>Will this suit a rental?</li>
      <li>What will cleaning involve?</li>
      <li>Will people actually use it?</li>
      <li>What common mistakes should I avoid?</li>
      <li>Do I need to buy anything yet?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The focus is on fit, function and household use.
    </p>

    <h2>Publication edit before publishing</h2>
    <p>
      Every new guide and every substantial update receives a publication edit before it
      is considered finished. This is a separate pass after the facts and structure are in
      place.
    </p>
    <p>
      The publication edit should:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>remove repeated ideas and formulaic wording</li>
      <li>improve the rhythm and transitions between sections</li>
      <li>use specific household observations instead of generic filler</li>
      <li>vary headings and section patterns where the subject allows</li>
      <li>apply Australian English and consistent terminology</li>
      <li>preserve factual accuracy, search intent and useful internal links</li>
      <li>keep safety cautions, disclosures and commercial boundaries intact</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The aim is publication-quality copy that sounds considered and natural, not wording
      designed to influence automated detection tools.
    </p>

    <h2>Product claims</h2>
    <p>
      We do not claim to personally test products unless that testing has actually happened
      and the article clearly explains it.
    </p>
    <p>
      We avoid:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>made-up reviews or personal experience</li>
      <li>testing that did not happen</li>
      <li>prices presented as current when they have not been checked</li>
      <li>unsupported best-product claims</li>
      <li>claims that one product is right for every household</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If a guide discusses a product type, it should explain what that type of product may
      help with, what to check before buying, and when it may not be suitable.
    </p>

    <h2>Affiliate links and commercial content</h2>
    <p>
      Some future pages may include affiliate links or commercial links. When affiliate
      links are added, the site should clearly disclose that relationship according to the
      site disclosure approach.
    </p>
    <p>
      Guides should still remain useful without requiring the reader to click a shopping
      link. We do not add affiliate disclaimers to articles that do not contain affiliate
      links.
    </p>

    <h2>Updating guides</h2>
    <p>
      Home products, retailers and household needs can change over time. Guides should be
      reviewed when information becomes outdated, when site structure changes, or when a
      guide needs clearer wording, better internal links or stronger practical checks.
    </p>

    <h2>The reader comes first</h2>
    <p>
      A guide should help the reader decide what is suitable for their home. That means it
      is acceptable for a guide to say:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>measure first</li>
      <li>check the space</li>
      <li>consider cleaning</li>
      <li>check rental limits</li>
      <li>avoid buying too much</li>
      <li>remove duplicates first</li>
      <li>do not buy yet if the problem is clutter</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The guide should serve the reader, not create a reason to spend.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
